Task 1

1-A - Plotting the location

To plot the location of an observation, cumsum() is used to sum up all accelerations to find velocities at each time point. Then to find the average velocities at each time point the averages of two consecutive velocities are computed. When the average velocities are summed again using cumsum() the location at each time point is obtained. Below is the code for the x location:

class=x_train[,1]
n=1
x=x_train[n, 2:ncol(x_train)]
x=t(x)
x=t(cumsum(x))
loc_x=cumsum((x[,1:ncol(x)-1]+x[,2:ncol(x)])/2)
plot(loc_x, main = "Class 6 X Axis", xlab = "Time", ylab = "X position")

plot(loc_y, main = "Class 6 Y Axis", xlab = "Time", ylab = "=Y position")

plot(loc_z, main = "Class 6 Z Axis", xlab = "Time", ylab = "Z position")

plot3D::scatter3D(loc_x,loc_y,loc_z,scale=TRUE,center=TRUE)

1-B - Choosing K for Nearest Neigbor

X, Y and Z locations of the observations are combined in one data table, using the cbind() function. Then the following code is run to determine the best k level for the nearest neighbor search. knn() function does the classification with “Euclidean” distance. For “Manhattan” distance kknn() function is used. Each function is run 50 times. There are 10 folds and 5 replications. From the resulting accuracy computation, Euclidean distance and k=3 level is chosen. I did not go with the Manhattan distance with k=1 level because k=1 can be misleading or overfitting. I also trust the result of the knn() function more.

combinedtrain=cbind(class,x_train[,-"class"], y_train[,-"class"], z_train[,-"class"])
trainclass=as.matrix(class)

k_levels=c(1,3,5,7)
nofReplications=1
nFolds=10
indices=TunePareto::generateCVRuns(trainclass,nofReplications,nFolds,stratified=TRUE)

cvresult=data.table()
for(i in 1:nofReplications) {
  thisReplication=indices[[i]]
  for(j in 1:nFolds){
    testindices=thisReplication[[j]]
    
    cvtrain=combinedtrain[-testindices,]        
    cvtest=combinedtrain[testindices,]
    class = cvtrain$class
    for(y in 1:length(k_levels)){
      param_k=k_levels[y]
      predict_knn=knn(cvtrain, cvtest, trainclass[-testindices], k = param_k)
      cvresult=rbind(cvresult,data.table(Replication=i,Fold=j, distance = "Euclidean", Klev=param_k,TestId=testindices,
                                         Predictions=as.numeric(as.character(predict_knn)),Real=trainclass[testindices]))
    } 
    for(z in 1:length(k_levels)){
      param_k=k_levels[z]
      predict_knn=kknn(class~., as.data.frame(cvtrain), as.data.frame(cvtest), k = param_k, distance = 1)
      cvresult=rbind(cvresult,data.table(Replication=i,Fold=j,distance = "Manhattan", Klev=param_k,TestId=testindices,
                                         Predictions=as.numeric(as.character(fitted(predict_knn))),Real=trainclass[testindices]))
      
    }
  }    
}
cvresult[,list(Accu=mean(Predictions==Real)),by=list(distance,Klev)]
##     distance Klev      Accu
## 1: Euclidean    1 0.9453125
## 2: Euclidean    3 0.9497768
## 3: Euclidean    5 0.9419643

## 5: Manhattan    1 0.9575893
## 6: Manhattan    3 0.8906250
## 7: Manhattan    5 0.8292411
## 8: Manhattan    7 0.7790179

2-B

Below the fit model and the coefficients of the model can be seen. Out of 96 possible coefficients for 96 variables (time), only 16 coefficients are non-zero. This can be because in the ECG data only times whit unusual peaks and troughs, are enough to identify the class, i.e. the situation of the patient. Of course the peaks and troughs could happen any time but since the data only contains 100 instances of both classes, there is a chance that the peaks and troughs happened mostly in these 16 points in time for all the data.

The fused lasso model is trained on the train data, using the optL1() function with 10-fold cross validation. The following lambda value is generated:

cvpenoptl1_diff$lambda

The test accuracy is higher than the train accuracy in this model, which probably happened by chance.
